// core.proof.tactics.arithmetic — decision procedures for
// arithmetic fragments.
//
// Every tactic in this file dispatches to Z3 or a specialised
// arithmetic routine and fails cleanly on goals outside its
// fragment. Ordering in a `first { … }` block should go from
// cheapest (omega) to most expensive (nlinarith).

// Linear arithmetic over integers.
//
// Decides quantifier-free formulas over `Int` with `+` / `-` /
// `<` / `<=` / `==` and integer multiplication by literal
// constants. Fails on nonlinear terms; use `nlinarith` for
// those.
//
// Complexity: polynomial in the number of constraints.
tactic omega() { omega }

// Linear arithmetic over rationals / reals.
//
// Same shape as `omega` but dispatches through Z3's LRA theory.
// Accepts `Float` / `Real` operands. Fails on nonlinear terms.
tactic linarith() { linarith }

// Nonlinear arithmetic over integers / reals.
//
// Extends `linarith` / `omega` to handle polynomial products.
// Slower than linear decision procedures but complete over
// decidable nonlinear fragments. Use sparingly in hot paths —
// `first { linarith; nlinarith }` is the standard dispatch.
tactic nlinarith() { nlinarith }

// Commutative-ring normalisation.
//
// Proves identities over commutative rings: `x + y == y + x`,
// `(a + b) * c == a*c + b*c`, etc. Internally normalises both
// sides to a canonical polynomial form and checks structural
// equality. Faster than the Z3 nonlinear path when the goal is
// a pure ring identity.
tactic ring() { ring }

// Field-axiom normalisation.
//
// Like `ring` but admits division by non-zero terms. Emits a
// side condition `denominator != 0` for each division in the
// goal; the proof closes only when the side conditions are
// dischargeable.
tactic field() { field }

// Numerical literal normalisation.
//
// Simplifies goals whose reasoning is pure arithmetic on
// literals — `2 + 3 == 5`, `10 * 0 == 0`, `3 < 5`. Cheapest of
// the arithmetic tactics; a good first step before `linarith`.
tactic norm_num() { norm_num }
